DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Metaphilosophy concerns the nature of philosophical inquiry itself, including
the methods philosophers use, the status of philosophical knowledge, and the
relationship between philosophy and other disciplines. This domain has seen
renewed interest in the 21st century, particularly through debates about
philosophical methodology, philosophical progress, and the diversity of
philosophical traditions. Major positions include: (1) Naturalistic approaches
that view philosophy as continuous with science (Williamson); (2) Conceptual
approaches emphasizing analysis and linguistic methods; (3) Pragmatist
approaches focused on the practical consequences of philosophical inquiry; and
(4) Pluralist approaches recognizing multiple valid methodologies and traditions.

Recent work (2022-2025) shows increased attention to global philosophy,
critiques of Eurocentrism in philosophical canons, and debates about ideal vs.
non-ideal theory. The question of philosophical progress remains contentious,
with some defending cumulative progress (Williamson, Lewin) and others
emphasizing historically situated, non-cumulative inquiry. Contemporary
metaphilosophy also grapples with the role of intuitions, experimental methods,
and the relationship between first-order philosophy and metaphilosophical
reflection.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides the overarching framework for understanding how literature
reviews function in philosophy. If philosophy has distinctive methods that differ
from empirical sciences, then philosophical literature reviews must be understood
in light of those methods. The debates about philosophical progress, the role of
the literature, and different metaphilosophical positions (naturalism, pragmatism,
etc.) directly inform how we should conceive the methodology and ethics of
literature reviews in philosophy.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While there is extensive work on philosophical methodology in general, there is
surprisingly little explicit reflection on the practice of literature review
itself in philosophy. The relationship between survey articles, overview entries
(SEP/IEP), and research monographs as forms of literature engagement is
under-theorized. Additionally, the differences between philosophical and
scientific literature reviews in terms of goals, methods, and epistemology
deserve more systematic attention.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis phase should highlight how different metaphilosophical positions
yield different conceptions of what literature reviews should accomplish. It
should also trace the recent globalizing turn in metaphilosophy and its
implications for whose work counts as "the literature." Key tensions to explore
include progress vs. history-dependency, unity vs. plurality of method, and
first-order vs. second-order approaches to philosophy.

