  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Lewin provides a systematic reconstruction of Kant's metaphilosophy, arguing that Kant developed an explicit account of philosophy's nature, aims, and methods. Kant distinguishes between philosophy as activity and philosophy as system, between the worldly concept and the scholastic concept of philosophy, and between philosophy as proper science and philosophy as idea. Lewin argues that Kant's critical project is fundamentally metaphilosophical: it investigates the conditions under which philosophy can be scientific. This analysis reveals eight elements of an "imperfect definition" of philosophy in Kant's work, including philosophy as an architectonic idea and reason as the absolute condition of philosophy.

  RELEVANCE: This paper demonstrates that metaphilosophical reflection has a distinguished historical pedigree and that Kant's critical philosophy centrally concerns the methodology of philosophy itself. For understanding literature reviews in philosophy, Kant's distinction between philosophy as activity and as system suggests that engaging with literature is not merely about surveying existing results but about participating in a distinctive form of rational activity. Kant's emphasis on systematic unity and architectonic structure implies that philosophical literature cannot be treated as a mere aggregation of results but must be understood in light of how individual contributions relate to systematic wholes.

  POSITION: Historical metaphilosophy showing that methodological reflection has been central to major philosophical projects.
  },
  keywords = {metaphilosophy, Kant, history-of-philosophy, High},
  abstract = {Abstract While the term “metaphilosophy” enjoys increasing popularity in Kant scholarship, it is neither clear what distinguishes a metaphilosophical theory from a philosophical one nor to what extent Kant’s philosophy contains metaphilosophical views. In the first part of the article, I will introduce a demarcation criterion and show how scholars fall prey to the fallacy of extension confusing Kant’s philosophical theories with his theories about philosophy. In the second part, I will analyze eight elements for an “imperfect definition” (KrV A731/B759) of philosophy outlining the scope of Kant’s explicit metaphilosophy against the backdrop of recent metaphilosophical research: (i) scientific concept of philosophy, (ii) philosophy as an activity, (iii) worldly concept, (iv) philosophy as a (proper and improper) science, (v) philosophy as an architectonic idea (archetype and ectypes), (vi) philosophy as a social practice and the appropriate holding-to-be-true (one or many true philosophies?), (vii) reason as the absolute condition and subject of philosophy, and (viii) methodology of philosophy. I will put these elements together for an attempt to give an imperfect definition of philosophy – something that Kant promised but never did – in the conclusion.},
